{"title_page": "Thrity Umrigar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian and  Parsi author}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = \n| imagesize   = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Thrity Umrigar\n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Mumbai]], India\n| alma_mater  = [[Bombay University]], [[Ohio State University]], [[Kent State University]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = [[Journalist]], [[novelist]], [[critic]], [[teacher]]\n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| genre       = \n| signature   =\n| website     = {{URL|umrigar.com}}\n}}\n'''Thrity Umrigar''' is an [[Indian-American]] journalist, critic, and novelist.\n\n==Early life==\nUmrigar was born in [[Mumbai]], India to a [[Parsi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookslut.com/features/2012_01_018505.php|title=Bookslut - An Interview with Thrity Umrigar|website=www.bookslut.com|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> family, and relocated to the United States at the age of 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/bio/|title=Bio|website=Thrity Umrigar official website|accessdate=14 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nUmrigar received a Bachelor of Science from [[Bombay University]], an M.A. From [[Ohio State University]], and a Ph.D. in English from [[Kent State University]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://bookpage.com/interviews/8766-thrity-umrigar#.WYkssdPytUQ|title=Thrity Umrigar|website=Bookpage|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref>\n\nShe has written for the ''[[Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]]'' and ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and regularly writes for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' 's book pages. She is the Armitage Professor of [[English language|English]] at [[Case Western Reserve University]] in [[Cleveland]]. She is active on the national lecture circuit.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thebetsywritersroom.com/programs/writers-on-the-bay-series/2015-2/|title=Writers-on-the-bay-series|website=BetsyWritersRoom|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.khabar.com/magazine/features/journalists_who_moonlight_as_fiction_writers.aspx|title=Journalists who moonlight as fiction writers|website=Khabar|access-date=2017-08-07}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n* ''Bombay Time'' (2001)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/bombay-time/|title=Bombay Time|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''First Darling of the Morning: Selected Memories of an Indian Childhood'' (2004)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/first-darling/|title=First Darling of the Morning|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''[[The Space Between Us (novel)|The Space Between Us]]'' (2006)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-space-between-us/|title=The Space Between Us|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''If Today Be Sweet'' (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/if-today-be-sweet/|title=If Today Be Sweet|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''The Weight of Heaven'' (2009)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-weight-of-heaven/|title=The Weight of Heaven|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''The World We Found'' (2012)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-world-we-found/|title=The World We Found|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''The Story Hour'' (2014)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-story-hour/|title=The Story Hour|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''Everybody's Son'' (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-secrets-between-us/|title=Everybody's Son|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref> \n* ''When I Carried You In My Belly'' (2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/when-i-carried-you-in-my-belly/|title=When I Carried You In My Belly|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-29}}</ref> \n* ''The Secrets Between Us'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://umrigar.com/the-secrets-between-us/|title=The Secrets Between Us|website=Thrity Umrigar|access-date=2018-05-13}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\n* 2000 - [[Nieman Fellowship]] for Journalism at [[Harvard University]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nieman.harvard.edu/NiemanFoundation/NiemanFellowships/MeetTheFellows/AlumniFellows.aspx#2000 |title=Archived copy |access-date=18 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140318212601/http://www.nieman.harvard.edu/NiemanFoundation/NiemanFellowships/MeetTheFellows/AlumniFellows.aspx#2000 |archive-date=18 March 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n* 2006 - Finalist for the [[PEN/Open Book]] award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.case.edu/faculty/thrity-umrigar/|title=Department of English|publisher=|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref>\n* 2009 - [[Cleveland Arts Prize in Literature]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clevelandartsprize.org/archive_year.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-03-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320171835/http://clevelandartsprize.org/archive_year.html |archivedate=2014-03-20 }}</ref>\n* 2013 - [[Lambda Literary Award]] in the Lesbian General Fiction category for her novel, ''The World We Found''<ref>[http://lgbtweekly.com/2013/06/04/25th-annual-lambda-literary-award-winners-announced/ \"25th annual Lambda Literary Award winners announced\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130610062409/http://lgbtweekly.com/2013/06/04/25th-annual-lambda-literary-award-winners-announced/ |date=10 June 2013 }}, ''LGBT Weekly'', 4 June 2013.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.umrigar.com/ Personal website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Umrigar, Thrity}}\n[[Category:American women writers of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Cat